def: Post information enabling patrons to wager on various races and sporting events. Assist in the operation of games such as keno and bingo. May operate random number-generating equipment and announce the numbers for patrons. Receive, verify, and record patrons’ wagers. Scan and process winning tickets presented by patrons and pay out winnings for those wagers.

title: Gambling service workers, all other
def: All gambling service workers not listed separately.

title: Motion picture projectionists
def: Set up and operate motion picture projection and related sound reproduction equipment.

title: Ushers, lobby attendants, etc
soc_title: Ushers, Lobby Attendants, and Ticket Takers
def: Assist patrons at entertainment events by performing duties, such as collecting admission tickets and passes from patrons, assisting in finding seats, searching for lost articles, and helping patrons locate such facilities as restrooms and telephones.

title: Miscellaneous entertainment attendants and related workers
soc_title: Miscellaneous Entertainment Attendants and Related Workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Amusement and recreation attendants
def: Perform a variety of attending duties at amusement or recreation facility. May schedule use of recreation facilities, maintain and provide equipment to participants of sporting events or recreational pursuits, or operate amusement concessions and rides.

title: Costume attendants
def: Select, fit, and take care of costumes for cast members, and aid entertainers. May assist with multiple costume changes during performances.

title: Locker room, coatroom, etc
soc_title: Locker Room, Coatroom, and Dressing Room Attendants
def: Provide personal items to patrons or customers in locker rooms, dressing rooms, or coatrooms.

title: Entertainment attendants and related workers, all other
soc_title: Entertainment Attendants and Related Workers, All Other
def: All entertainment attendants and related workers not listed separately.

title: Funeral service workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Embalmers and crematory operators
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Embalmers
def: Prepare bodies for interment in conformity with legal requirements.

title: Crematory operators
def: Operate crematory equipment to reduce human or animal remains to bone fragments in accordance with state and local regulations. Duties may include preparing the body for cremation and performing general maintenance on crematory equipment. May use traditional flame-based cremation, calcination, or alkaline hydrolysis.

title: Funeral attendants
def: Perform a variety of tasks during funeral, such as placing casket in parlor or chapel prior to service, arranging floral offerings or lights around casket, directing or escorting mourners, closing casket, and issuing and storing funeral equipment.

title: Morticians, undertakers, etc
def: Perform various tasks to arrange and direct individual funeral services, such as coordinating transportation of body to mortuary, interviewing family or other authorized person to arrange details, selecting pallbearers, aiding with the selection of officials for religious rites, and providing transportation for mourners. Excludes “Funeral Home Managers” (11-9171).

title: Personal appearance workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Barbers, hairdressers, etc
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Barbers
def: Provide barbering services, such as cutting, trimming, shampooing, and styling hair; trimming beards; or giving shaves.

title: Hairdressers, hairstylists, etc
def: Provide beauty services, such as cutting, coloring, and styling hair, and massaging and treating scalp. May shampoo hair, apply makeup, dress wigs, remove hair, and provide nail and skincare services. Excludes “Makeup Artists, Theatrical and Performance” (39-5091), “Manicurists and Pedicurists” (39-5092), and “Skincare Specialists” (39-5094).

title: Miscellaneous personal appearance workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Makeup artists, theatrical and performance
def: Apply makeup to performers to reflect period, setting, and situation of their role.

title: Manicurists and pedicurists
def: Clean and shape customers’ fingernails and toenails. May polish or decorate nails.

title: Shampooers
def: Shampoo and rinse customers’ hair.

title: Skincare specialists
def: Provide skincare treatments to face and body to enhance an individual’s appearance. Includes electrologists and laser hair removal specialists.

title: Baggage porters, bellhops, etc
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Baggage porters and bellhops
def: Handle baggage for travelers at transportation terminals or for guests at hotels or similar establishments.

title: Concierges
def: Assist patrons at hotel, apartment, or office building with personal services. May take messages; arrange or give advice on transportation, business services, or entertainment; or monitor guest requests for housekeeping and maintenance.

title: Tour and travel guides
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Tour and travel guides
def: No job definition found.

title: Other personal care and service workers
soc_title: Other Personal Care and Service Workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Childcare workers
def: Attend to children at schools, businesses, private households, and childcare institutions. Perform a variety of tasks, such as dressing, feeding, bathing, and overseeing play. Excludes “Preschool Teachers, Except Special Education” (25-2011) and “Teaching Assistants, Preschool, Elementary, Middle, and Secondary School, Except Special Education” (25-9042).

title: Recreation and fitness workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Exercise trainers and group fitness instructors
soc_title: Exercise Trainers and Group Fitness Instructors
def: Instruct or coach groups or individuals in exercise activities for the primary purpose of personal fitness. Demonstrate techniques and form, observe participants, and explain to them corrective measures necessary to improve their skills. Develop and implement individualized approaches to exercise. Excludes “Educational Instruction and Library Occupations” (25-0000), “Coaches and Scouts” (27-2022), and “Athletic Trainers” (29-9091).

title: Recreation workers
def: Conduct recreation activities with groups in public, private, or volunteer agencies or recreation facilities. Organize and promote activities, such as arts and crafts, sports, games, music, dramatics, social recreation, camping, and hobbies, taking into account the needs and interests of individual members.

title: Residential advisors
def: Coordinate activities in resident facilities in secondary school and college dormitories, group homes, or similar establishments. Order supplies and determine need for maintenance, repairs, and furnishings. May maintain household records and assign rooms. May assist residents with problem solving or refer them to counseling resources.

title: Personal care and service workers, all other
soc_title: Personal Care and Service Workers, All Other
def: All personal care and service workers not listed separately.

title: Sales and related
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Supervisors of sales workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: First-line supervisors of retail sales workers
soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Retail Sales Workers
def: Directly supervise and coordinate activities of retail sales workers in an establishment or department. Duties may include management functions, such as purchasing, budgeting, accounting, and personnel work, in addition to supervisory duties.

title: First-line supervisors of non-retail sales workers
soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Non-Retail Sales Workers
def: Directly supervise and coordinate activities of sales workers other than retail sales workers. May perform duties such as budgeting, accounting, and personnel work, in addition to supervisory duties.

title: Retail sales workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Cashiers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Cashiers
def: Receive and disburse money in establishments other than financial institutions. May use electronic scanners, cash registers, or related equipment. May process credit or debit card transactions and validate checks. Excludes “Gambling Change Persons and Booth Cashiers” (41-2012).

title: Gambling change persons and booth cashiers
soc_title: Gambling Change Persons and Booth Cashiers
def: Exchange coins, tokens, and chips for patrons’ money. May issue payoffs and obtain customer’s signature on receipt. May operate a booth in the slot machine area and furnish change persons with money bank at the start of the shift, or count and audit money in drawers. Excludes “Cashiers” (41-2011).

title: Counter and rental clerks and parts salespersons
soc_title: Counter and Rental Clerks and Parts Salespersons
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Counter and rental clerks
def: Receive orders, generally in person, for repairs, rentals, and services. May describe available options, compute cost, and accept payment. Excludes “Fast Food and Counter Workers” (35-3023), “Hotel, Motel, and Resort Desk Clerks” (43-4081), “Order Clerks” (43-4151), and “Reservation and Transportation Ticket Agents and Travel Clerks” (43-4181).

title: Parts salespersons
def: Sell spare and replacement parts and equipment in repair shop or parts store.

title: Retail salespersons
def: Sell merchandise, such as furniture, motor vehicles, appliances, or apparel to consumers. Excludes “Cashiers” (41-2011).

title: Sales representatives, services
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Advertising sales agents
def: Sell or solicit advertising space, time, or media in publications, signage, TV, radio, or Internet establishments or public spaces.

title: Insurance sales agents
def: Sell life, property, casualty, health, automotive, or other types of insurance. May refer clients to independent brokers, work as an independent broker, or be employed by an insurance company.

title: Securities, commodities, etc
soc_title: Securities, Commodities, and Financial Services Sales Agents
def: Buy and sell securities or commodities in investment and trading firms, or provide financial services to businesses and individuals. May advise customers about stocks, bonds, mutual funds, commodities, and market conditions.

title: Travel agents
def: Plan and sell transportation and accommodations for customers. Determine destination, modes of transportation, travel dates, costs, and accommodations required. May also describe, plan, and arrange itineraries and sell tour packages. May assist in resolving clients’ travel problems.

title: Sales representatives of services, except advertising, etc
soc_title: Sales Representatives of Services, Except Advertising, Insurance, Financial Services, and Travel
def: Sell services to individuals or businesses. May describe options or resolve client problems. Excludes “Advertising Sales Agents” (41-3011), “Insurance Sales Agents” (41-3021), “Securities, Commodities, and Financial Services Sales Agents” (41-3031), “Travel Agents” (41-3041), “Sales Representatives, Wholesale and Manufacturing” (41-4010), and “Telemarketers” (41-9041).

title: Sales representatives, wholesale and manufacturing
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Sales representatives, wholesale and manufacturing, etc
soc_title: Sales Representatives, Wholesale and Manufacturing, Technical and Scientific Products
def: Sell goods for wholesalers or manufacturers where technical or scientific knowledge is required in such areas as biology, engineering, chemistry, and electronics, normally obtained from at least 2 years of postsecondary education. Excludes “Sales Engineers” (41-9031).

title: Sales representatives, wholesale and manufacturing, etc
soc_title: Sales Representatives, Wholesale and Manufacturing, Except Technical and Scientific Products
def: Sell goods for wholesalers or manufacturers to businesses or groups of individuals. Work requires substantial knowledge of items sold.

title: Other sales and related workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Models, demonstrators, etc
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Demonstrators and product promoters
def: Demonstrate merchandise and answer questions for the purpose of creating public interest in buying the product. May sell demonstrated merchandise.

title: Models
def: Model garments or other apparel and accessories for prospective buyers at fashion shows, private showings, or retail establishments. May pose for photos to be used in magazines or advertisements. May pose as subject for paintings, sculptures, and other types of artistic expression.

title: Real estate brokers and sales agents
soc_title: Real Estate Brokers and Sales Agents
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Real estate brokers
def: Operate real estate office, or work for commercial real estate firm, overseeing real estate transactions. Other duties usually include selling real estate or renting properties and arranging loans.

title: Real estate sales agents
def: Rent, buy, or sell property for clients. Perform duties such as study property listings, interview prospective clients, accompany clients to property site, discuss conditions of sale, and draw up real estate contracts. Includes agents who represent buyer.

title: Sales engineers
def: Sell business goods or services, the selling of which requires a technical background equivalent to a baccalaureate degree in engineering. Excludes “Engineers” (17-2011 through 17-2199) whose primary function is not marketing or sales.

title: Telemarketers
def: Solicit donations or orders for goods or services over the telephone.

title: Miscellaneous sales and related workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Door-to-door sales workers, news and street vendors, etc
soc_title: Door-to-Door Sales Workers, News and Street Vendors, and Related Workers
def: Sell goods or services door-to-door or on the street.

title: Sales and related workers, all other
soc_title: Sales and Related Workers, All Other
def: All sales and related workers not listed separately.

title: Office and administrative support
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Supervisors of office and administrative support workers
soc_title: Supervisors of Office and Administrative Support Workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: First-line supervisors of office and administrative support workers
soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Office and Administrative Support Workers
def: Directly supervise and coordinate the activities of clerical and administrative support workers.

title: Communications equipment operators
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Switchboard operators, including answering service
def: Operate telephone business systems equipment or switchboards to relay incoming, outgoing, and interoffice calls. May supply information to callers and record messages.

title: Telephone operators
def: Provide information by accessing alphabetical, geographical, or other directories. Assist customers with special billing requests, such as charges to a third party and credits or refunds for incorrectly dialed numbers or bad connections. May handle emergency calls and assist children or people with physical disabilities to make telephone calls.

title: Communications equipment operators, all other
def: All communications equipment operators not listed separately.

title: Financial clerks
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Bill and account collectors
def: Locate and notify customers of delinquent accounts by mail, telephone, or personal visit to solicit payment. Duties include receiving payment and posting amount to customer’s account, preparing statements to credit department if customer fails to respond, initiating repossession proceedings or service disconnection, and keeping records of collection and status of accounts.

title: Billing and posting clerks
def: Compile, compute, and record billing, accounting, statistical, and other numerical data for billing purposes. Prepare billing invoices for services rendered or for delivery or shipment of goods. Excludes “Medical Records Specialists” (29-2072).

title: Bookkeeping, accounting, etc
def: Compute, classify, and record numerical data to keep financial records complete. Perform any combination of routine calculating, posting, and verifying duties to obtain primary financial data for use in maintaining accounting records. May also check the accuracy of figures, calculations, and postings pertaining to business transactions recorded by other workers. Excludes “Payroll and Timekeeping Clerks” (43-3051).

title: Gambling cage workers
def: In a gambling establishment, conduct financial transactions for patrons. Accept patron’s credit application and verify credit references to provide check-cashing authorization or to establish house credit accounts. May reconcile daily summaries of transactions to balance books. May sell gambling chips, tokens, or tickets to patrons, or to other workers for resale to patrons. May convert gambling chips, tokens, or tickets to currency upon patron’s request. May use a cash register or computer to record transaction.

title: Payroll and timekeeping clerks
def: Compile and record employee time and payroll data. May compute employees’ time worked, production, and commission. May compute and post wages and deductions, or prepare paychecks. Excludes “Bookkeeping, Accounting, and Auditing Clerks” (43-3031).

title: Procurement clerks
def: Compile information and records to draw up purchase orders for procurement of materials and services. Excludes “Wholesale and Retail Buyers, Except Farm Products” (13-1022).

title: Tellers
def: Receive and pay out money. Keep records of money and negotiable instruments involved in a financial institution’s various transactions.

title: Financial clerks, all other
def: All financial clerks not listed separately.

title: Information and record clerks
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Brokerage clerks
def: Perform duties related to the purchase, sale, or holding of securities. Duties include writing orders for stock purchases or sales, computing transfer taxes, verifying stock transactions, accepting and delivering securities, tracking stock price fluctuations, computing equity, distributing dividends, and keeping records of daily transactions and holdings.

title: Correspondence clerks
def: Compose letters or electronic correspondence in reply to requests for merchandise, damage claims, credit and other information, delinquent accounts, incorrect billings, or unsatisfactory services. Duties may include gathering data to formulate reply and preparing correspondence.

title: Court, municipal, etc
def: Perform clerical duties for courts of law, municipalities, or governmental licensing agencies and bureaus. May prepare docket of cases to be called; secure information for judges and court; prepare draft agendas or bylaws for town or city council; answer official correspondence; keep fiscal records and accounts; issue licenses or permits; and record data, administer tests, or collect fees. Clerks of Court are classified in “Managers, All Other” (11-9199).

title: Credit authorizers, checkers, etc
def: Authorize credit charges against customers’ accounts. Investigate history and credit standing of individuals or business establishments applying for credit. May interview applicants to obtain personal and financial data, determine credit worthiness, process applications, and notify customers of acceptance or rejection of credit.

title: Customer service representatives
def: Interact with customers to provide basic or scripted information in response to routine inquiries about products and services. May handle and resolve general complaints. Excludes individuals whose duties are primarily installation, sales, repair, and technical support.

title: Eligibility interviewers, government programs
def: Determine eligibility of persons applying to receive assistance from government programs and agency resources, such as welfare, unemployment benefits, social security, and public housing.

title: File clerks
def: File correspondence, cards, invoices, receipts, and other records in alphabetical or numerical order or according to the filing system used. Locate and remove material from file when requested.

title: Hotel, motel, etc
soc_title: Hotel, Motel, and Resort Desk Clerks
def: Accommodate hotel, motel, and resort patrons by registering and assigning rooms to guests, issuing room keys or cards, transmitting and receiving messages, keeping records of occupied rooms and guests’ accounts, making and confirming reservations, and presenting statements to and collecting payments from departing guests.

title: Interviewers, except eligibility and loan
def: Interview persons by telephone, mail, in person, or by other means for the purpose of completing forms, applications, or questionnaires. Ask specific questions, record answers, and assist persons with completing form. May sort, classify, and file forms.

title: Library assistants, clerical
def: Compile records, and sort, shelve, issue, and receive library materials such as books, electronic media, pictures, cards, slides and microfilm. Locate library materials for loan and replace material in shelving area, stacks, or files according to identification number and title. Register patrons to permit them to borrow books, periodicals, and other library materials. Excludes “Library Technicians” (25-4031).

title: Loan interviewers and clerks
def: Interview loan applicants to elicit information; investigate applicants’ backgrounds and verify references; prepare loan request papers; and forward findings, reports, and documents to appraisal department. Review loan papers to ensure completeness, and complete transactions between loan establishment, borrowers, and sellers upon approval of loan.

title: New accounts clerks
def: Interview persons desiring to open accounts in financial institutions. Explain account services available to prospective customers and assist them in preparing applications.

title: Order clerks
def: Receive and process incoming orders for materials, merchandise, classified ads, or services such as repairs, installations, or rental of facilities. Generally receives orders via mail, phone, fax, or other electronic means. Duties include informing customers of receipt, prices, shipping dates, and delays; preparing contracts; and handling complaints. Excludes “Dispatchers, Except Police, Fire, and Ambulance” (43-5032) who both dispatch and take orders for services.

title: Human resources assistants, except payroll and timekeeping
soc_title: Human Resources Assistants, Except Payroll and Timekeeping
def: Compile and keep personnel records. Record data for each employee, such as address, weekly earnings, absences, amount of sales or production, supervisory reports, and date of and reason for termination. May prepare reports for employment records, file employment records, or search employee files and furnish information to authorized persons.

title: Receptionists and information clerks
def: Answer inquiries and provide information to the general public, customers, visitors, and other interested parties regarding activities conducted at establishment and location of departments, offices, and employees within the organization. Excludes “Switchboard Operators, Including Answering Service” (43-2011).

title: Reservation and transportation ticket agents and travel clerks
soc_title: Reservation and Transportation Ticket Agents and Travel Clerks
def: Make and confirm reservations for transportation or lodging, or sell transportation tickets. May check baggage and direct passengers to designated concourse, pier, or track; deliver tickets and contact individuals and groups to inform them of package tours; or provide tourists with travel or transportation information. Excludes "Cashiers” (41-2011), "Travel Agents” (41-3041), and "Hotel, Motel, and Resort Desk Clerks” (43-4081) who sell tickets for local transportation.

title: Information and record clerks, all other
soc_title: Information and Record Clerks, All Other
def: All information and record clerks not listed separately.

title: Material recording, scheduling, etc
soc_title: Material Recording, Scheduling, Dispatching, and Distributing Workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Cargo and freight agents
def: Expedite and route movement of incoming and outgoing cargo and freight shipments in airline, train, and trucking terminals and shipping docks. Take orders from customers and arrange pickup of freight and cargo for delivery to loading platform. Prepare and examine bills of lading to determine shipping charges and tariffs.

title: Couriers and messengers
def: Pick up and deliver messages, documents, packages, and other items between offices or departments within an establishment or directly to other business concerns, traveling by foot, bicycle, motorcycle, automobile, or public conveyance. Excludes “Light Truck Drivers” (53-3033).

title: Dispatchers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Public safety telecommunicators
def: Operate telephone, radio, or other communication systems to receive and communicate requests for emergency assistance at 9-1-1 public safety answering points and emergency operations centers. Take information from the public and other sources regarding crimes, threats, disturbances, acts of terrorism, fires, medical emergencies, and other public safety matters. May coordinate and provide information to law enforcement and emergency response personnel. May access sensitive databases and other information sources as needed. May provide additional instructions to callers based on knowledge of and certification in law enforcement, fire, or emergency medical procedures.

title: Dispatchers, except police, etc
soc_title: Dispatchers, Except Police, Fire, and Ambulance
def: Schedule and dispatch workers, work crews, equipment, or service vehicles for conveyance of materials, freight, or passengers, or for normal installation, service, or emergency repairs rendered outside the place of business. Duties may include using radio, telephone, or computer to transmit assignments and compiling statistics and reports on work progress.

title: Meter readers, utilities
def: Read meter and record consumption of electricity, gas, water, or steam.

title: Postal service workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Postal service clerks
def: Perform any combination of tasks in a United States Postal Service (USPS) post office, such as receive letters and parcels; sell postage and revenue stamps, postal cards, and stamped envelopes; fill out and sell money orders; place mail in pigeon holes of mail rack or in bags; and examine mail for correct postage. Includes postal service clerks employed by USPS contractors.

title: Postal service mail carriers
def: Sort and deliver mail for the United States Postal Service (USPS). Deliver mail on established route by vehicle or on foot. Includes postal service mail carriers employed by USPS contractors.

title: Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc
soc_title: Postal Service Mail Sorters, Processors, and Processing Machine Operators
def: Prepare incoming and outgoing mail for distribution for the United States Postal Service (USPS). Examine, sort, and route mail. Load, operate, and occasionally adjust and repair mail processing, sorting, and canceling machinery. Keep records of shipments, pouches, and sacks, and perform other duties related to mail handling within the postal service. Includes postal service mail sorters and processors employed by USPS contractors. Excludes “Postal Service Clerks” (43-5051) and “Postal Service Mail Carriers” (43-5052).

title: Production, planning, etc
def: Coordinate and expedite the flow of work and materials within or between departments of an establishment according to production schedule. Duties include reviewing and distributing production, work, and shipment schedules; conferring with department supervisors to determine progress of work and completion dates; and compiling reports on progress of work, inventory levels, costs, and production problems. Excludes “Project Management Specialists” (13-1082) and “Weighers, Measurers, Checkers, and Samplers, Recordkeeping” (43-5111).

title: Shipping, receiving, etc
def: Verify and maintain records on incoming and outgoing shipments involving inventory. Duties include verifying and recording incoming merchandise or material and arranging for the transportation of products. May prepare items for shipment. Excludes “Weighers, Measurers, Checkers, and Samplers, Recordkeeping” (43-5111), “Mail Clerks and Mail Machine Operators, except Postal Service” (43-9051), and “Stockers and Order Fillers” (53-7065).

title: Weighers, measurers, etc
soc_title: Weighers, Measurers, Checkers, and Samplers, Recordkeeping
def: Weigh, measure, and check materials, supplies, and equipment for the purpose of keeping relevant records. Duties are primarily clerical by nature. Includes workers who collect and keep record of samples of products or materials. Excludes “Inspectors, Testers, Sorters, Samplers, and Weighers” (51-9061).

title: Secretaries and administrative assistants
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Executive secretaries and executive administrative assistants
soc_title: Executive Secretaries and Executive Administrative Assistants
def: Provide high-level administrative support by conducting research, preparing statistical reports, and handling information requests, as well as performing routine administrative functions such as preparing correspondence, receiving visitors, arranging conference calls, and scheduling meetings. May also train and supervise lower-level clerical staff. Excludes “Secretaries” (43-6012 through 43-6014).

title: Legal secretaries and administrative assistants
def: Perform secretarial duties using legal terminology, procedures, and documents. Prepare legal papers and correspondence, such as summonses, complaints, motions, and subpoenas. May also assist with legal research.

title: Medical secretaries and administrative assistants
def: Perform secretarial duties using specific knowledge of medical terminology and hospital, clinic, or laboratory procedures. Duties may include scheduling appointments, billing patients, and compiling and recording medical charts, reports, and correspondence.

title: Secretaries and administrative assistants, except legal, etc
soc_title: Secretaries and Administrative Assistants, Except Legal, Medical, and Executive
def: Perform routine administrative functions such as drafting correspondence, scheduling appointments, organizing and maintaining paper and electronic files, or providing information to callers. Excludes legal, medical, and executive secretaries (43-6011 through 43-6013).

title: Other office and administrative support workers
soc_title: Other Office and Administrative Support Workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Data entry and information processing workers
soc_title: Data Entry and Information Processing Workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Data entry keyers
def: Operate data entry device, such as keyboard or photo composing perforator. Duties may include verifying data and preparing materials for printing. Excludes “Word Processors and Typists” (43-9022).

title: Word processors and typists
def: Use word processor, computer, or typewriter to type letters, reports, forms, or other material from rough draft, corrected copy, or voice recording. May perform other clerical duties as assigned. Excludes “Court Reporters and Simultaneous Captioners” (27-3092), “Medical Transcriptionists” (31-9094), “Secretaries and Administrative Assistants” (43-6010), and “Data Entry Keyers” (43-9021).

title: Desktop publishers
def: Format typescript and graphic elements using computer software to produce publication-ready material.

title: Insurance claims and policy processing clerks
soc_title: Insurance Claims and Policy Processing Clerks
def: Process new insurance policies, modifications to existing policies, and claims forms. Obtain information from policyholders to verify the accuracy and completeness of information on claims forms, applications and related documents, and company records. Update existing policies and company records to reflect changes requested by policyholders and insurance company representatives. Excludes “Claims Adjusters, Examiners, and Investigators” (13-1031).

title: Mail clerks and mail machine operators, except postal service
soc_title: Mail Clerks and Mail Machine Operators, Except Postal Service
def: Prepare incoming and outgoing mail for distribution. Time-stamp, open, read, sort, and route incoming mail; and address, seal, stamp, fold, stuff, and affix postage to outgoing mail or packages. Duties may also include keeping necessary records and completed forms.

title: Office clerks, general
def: Perform duties too varied and diverse to be classified in any specific office clerical occupation, requiring knowledge of office systems and procedures. Clerical duties may be assigned in accordance with the office procedures of individual establishments and may include a combination of answering telephones, bookkeeping, typing or word processing, office machine operation, and filing.

title: Office machine operators, except computer
def: Operate one or more of a variety of office machines, such as photocopying, photographic, and duplicating machines, or other office machines. Excludes “Billing and Posting Clerks” (43-3021) and “Mail Clerks and Mail Machine Operators, Except Postal Service” (43-9051).

title: Proofreaders and copy markers
def: Read transcript or proof type setup to detect and mark for correction any grammatical, typographical, or compositional errors. Excludes workers whose primary duty is editing copy. Includes proofreaders of braille.

title: Statistical assistants
def: Compile and compute data according to statistical formulas for use in statistical studies. May perform actuarial computations and compile charts and graphs for use by actuaries. Includes actuarial clerks.

title: Office and administrative support workers, all other
soc_title: Office and Administrative Support Workers, All Other
def: All office and administrative support workers not listed separately.

title: Farming, fishing, etc
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Supervisors of farming, fishing, etc
soc_title: Supervisors of Farming, Fishing, and Forestry Workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: First-line supervisors of farming, fishing, etc
soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Farming, Fishing, and Forestry Workers
def: Directly supervise and coordinate the activities of agricultural, forestry, aquacultural, and related workers. Excludes “First-Line Supervisors of Landscaping, Lawn Service, and Groundskeeping Workers” (37-1012).

title: Agricultural workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Agricultural inspectors
def: Inspect agricultural commodities, processing equipment, and facilities, and fish and logging operations, to ensure compliance with regulations and laws governing health, quality, and safety.

title: Animal breeders
def: Select and breed animals according to their genealogy, characteristics, and offspring. May require knowledge of artificial insemination techniques and equipment use. May involve keeping records on heats, birth intervals, or pedigree. Excludes “Animal Scientists” (19-1011) whose primary function is research and “Animal Caretakers” (39-2021) who may occasionally breed animals as part of their other caretaking duties.

title: Graders and sorters, agricultural products
def: Grade, sort, or classify unprocessed food and other agricultural products by size, weight, color, or condition. Excludes “Agricultural Inspectors” (45-2011).

title: Miscellaneous agricultural workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Agricultural equipment operators
def: Drive and control equipment to support agricultural activities such as tilling soil; planting, cultivating, and harvesting crops; feeding and herding livestock; or removing animal waste. May perform tasks such as crop baling or hay bucking. May operate stationary equipment to perform post-harvest tasks such as husking, shelling, threshing, and ginning.

title: Farmworkers and laborers, crop, etc
soc_title: Farmworkers and Laborers, Crop, Nursery, and Greenhouse
def: Manually plant, cultivate, and harvest vegetables, fruits, nuts, horticultural specialties, and field crops. Use hand tools, such as shovels, trowels, hoes, tampers, pruning hooks, shears, and knives. Duties may include tilling soil and applying fertilizers; transplanting, weeding, thinning, or pruning crops; applying pesticides; or cleaning, grading, sorting, packing, and loading harvested products. May construct trellises, repair fences and farm buildings, or participate in irrigation activities. Excludes “Pesticide Handlers, Sprayers, and Applicators, Vegetation” (37-3012), “Graders and Sorters, Agricultural Products” (45-2041), and “Forest, Conservation, and Logging Workers” (45-4011 through 45-4029).

title: Farmworkers, farm, etc
soc_title: Farmworkers, Farm, Ranch, and Aquacultural Animals
def: Attend to live farm, ranch, open range or aquacultural animals that may include cattle, sheep, swine, goats, horses and other equines, poultry, rabbits, finfish, shellfish, and bees. Attend to animals produced for animal products, such as meat, fur, skins, feathers, eggs, milk, and honey. Duties may include feeding, watering, herding, grazing, milking, castrating, branding, de-beaking, weighing, catching, and loading animals. May maintain records on animals; examine animals to detect diseases and injuries; assist in birth deliveries; and administer medications, vaccinations, or insecticides as appropriate. May clean and maintain animal housing areas. Includes workers who shear wool from sheep and collect eggs in hatcheries.

title: Agricultural workers, all other
def: All agricultural workers not listed separately.

title: Fishing and hunting workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Fishing and hunting workers
def: Hunt, trap, catch, or gather wild animals or aquatic animals and plants. May use nets, traps, or other equipment. May haul catch onto ship or other vessel. Aquacultural laborers who work on fish farms are included in “Farmworkers, Farm, Ranch, and Aquacultural Animals” (45-2093).

title: Forest, conservation, etc
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Forest and conservation workers
def: Under supervision, perform manual labor necessary to develop, maintain, or protect areas such as forests, forested areas, woodlands, wetlands, and rangelands through such activities as raising and transporting seedlings; combating insects, pests, and diseases harmful to plant life; and building structures to control water, erosion, and leaching of soil. Includes forester aides, seedling pullers, tree planters, and gatherers of nontimber forestry products such as pine straw.

title: Logging workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Fallers
def: Use axes or chainsaws to fell trees using knowledge of tree characteristics and cutting techniques to control direction of fall and minimize tree damage.

title: Logging equipment operators
def: Drive logging tractor or wheeled vehicle equipped with one or more accessories, such as bulldozer blade, frontal shear, grapple, logging arch, cable winches, hoisting rack, or crane boom, to fell tree; to skid, load, unload, or stack logs; or to pull stumps or clear brush. Includes operating stand-alone logging machines, such as log chippers. Logging truck drivers are included in “Heavy and Tractor-Trailer Truck Drivers” (53-3032).

title: Log graders and scalers
def: Grade logs or estimate the marketable content or value of logs or pulpwood in sorting yards, millpond, log deck, or similar locations. Inspect logs for defects or measure logs to determine volume. Excludes “Buyers and Purchasing Agents, Farm Products” (13-1021).

title: Logging workers, all other
def: All logging workers not listed separately.

title: Construction and extraction
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Supervisors of construction and extraction workers
soc_title: Supervisors of Construction and Extraction Workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: First-line supervisors of construction trades and extraction workers
soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Construction Trades and Extraction Workers
def: Directly supervise and coordinate activities of construction or extraction workers.

title: Construction trades workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Boilermakers
def: Construct, assemble, maintain, and repair stationary steam boilers and boiler house auxiliaries. Align structures or plate sections to assemble boiler frame tanks or vats, following blueprints. Work involves use of hand and power tools, plumb bobs, levels, wedges, dogs, or turnbuckles. Assist in testing assembled vessels. Direct cleaning of boilers and boiler furnaces. Inspect and repair boiler fittings, such as safety valves, regulators, automatic-control mechanisms, water columns, and auxiliary machines.

title: Brickmasons, blockmasons, etc
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Brickmasons and blockmasons
def: Lay and bind building materials, such as brick, structural tile, concrete block, cinder block, glass block, and terra-cotta block, with mortar and other substances, to construct or repair walls, partitions, arches, sewers, and other structures. Installers of mortarless segmental concrete masonry wall units are classified in “Landscaping and Groundskeeping Workers” (37-3011). Excludes “Stonemasons” (47-2022).

title: Stonemasons
def: Build stone structures, such as piers, walls, and abutments. Lay walks, curbstones, or special types of masonry for vats, tanks, and floors.

title: Carpenters
def: Construct, erect, install, or repair structures and fixtures made of wood and comparable materials, such as concrete forms; building frameworks, including partitions, joists, studding, and rafters; and wood stairways, window and door frames, and hardwood floors. May also install cabinets, siding, drywall, and batt or roll insulation. Includes brattice builders who build doors or brattices (ventilation walls or partitions) in underground passageways.

title: Carpet, floor, etc
soc_title: Carpet, Floor, and Tile Installers and Finishers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Carpet installers
def: Lay and install carpet from rolls or blocks on floors. Install padding and trim flooring materials. Excludes “Floor Layers, Except Carpet, Wood, and Hard Tiles” (47-2042).

title: Floor layers, except carpet, etc
soc_title: Floor Layers, Except Carpet, Wood, and Hard Tiles
def: Apply blocks, strips, or sheets of shock-absorbing, sound-deadening, or decorative coverings to floors.

title: Floor sanders and finishers
def: Scrape and sand wooden floors to smooth surfaces using floor scraper and floor sanding machine, and apply coats of finish.

title: Tile and stone setters
def: Apply hard tile, stone, and comparable materials to walls, floors, ceilings, countertops, and roof decks.

title: Cement masons, concrete finishers, etc
soc_title: Cement Masons, Concrete Finishers, and Terrazzo Workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Cement masons and concrete finishers
def: Smooth and finish surfaces of poured concrete, such as floors, walks, sidewalks, roads, or curbs using a variety of hand and power tools. Align forms for sidewalks, curbs, or gutters; patch voids; and use saws to cut expansion joints. Installers of mortarless segmental concrete masonry wall units are classified in “Landscaping and Groundskeeping Workers” (37-3011).

title: Terrazzo workers and finishers
def: Apply a mixture of cement, sand, pigment, or marble chips to floors, stairways, and cabinet fixtures to fashion durable and decorative surfaces.

title: Construction laborers
def: Perform tasks involving physical labor at construction sites. May operate hand and power tools of all types: air hammers, earth tampers, cement mixers, small mechanical hoists, surveying and measuring equipment, and a variety of other equipment and instruments. May clean and prepare sites, dig trenches, set braces to support the sides of excavations, erect scaffolding, and clean up rubble, debris, and other waste materials. May assist other craft workers. Construction laborers who primarily assist a particular craft worker are classified under “Helpers, Construction Trades” (47-3010). Excludes “Hazardous Materials Removal Workers” (47-4041).

title: Construction equipment operators
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Paving, surfacing, etc
soc_title: Paving, Surfacing, and Tamping Equipment Operators
def: Operate equipment used for applying concrete, asphalt, or other materials to road beds, parking lots, or airport runways and taxiways or for tamping gravel, dirt, or other materials. Includes concrete and asphalt paving machine operators, form tampers, tamping machine operators, and stone spreader operators.

title: Pile driver operators
def: Operate pile drivers mounted on skids, barges, crawler treads, or locomotive cranes to drive pilings for retaining walls, bulkheads, and foundations of structures such as buildings, bridges, and piers.

title: Operating engineers and other construction equipment operators
soc_title: Operating Engineers and Other Construction Equipment Operators
def: Operate one or several types of power construction equipment, such as motor graders, bulldozers, scrapers, compressors, pumps, derricks, shovels, tractors, or front-end loaders to excavate, move, and grade earth, erect structures, or pour concrete or other hard surface pavement. May repair and maintain equipment in addition to other duties. Excludes “Extraction Workers” (47-5000) and “Crane and Tower Operators” (53-7021).

title: Drywall installers, ceiling tile installers, etc
soc_title: Drywall Installers, Ceiling Tile Installers, and Tapers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Drywall and ceiling tile installers
def: Apply plasterboard or other wallboard to ceilings or interior walls of buildings. Apply or mount acoustical tiles or blocks, strips, or sheets of shock-absorbing materials to ceilings and walls of buildings to reduce or reflect sound. Materials may be of decorative quality. Includes lathers who fasten wooden, metal, or rockboard lath to walls, ceilings, or partitions of buildings to provide support base for plaster, fireproofing, or acoustical material. Excludes “Carpenters” (47-2031), “Carpet Installers” (47-2041), and “Tile and Stone Setters” (47-2044).

title: Tapers
def: Seal joints between plasterboard or other wallboard to prepare wall surface for painting or papering.

title: Electricians
def: Install, maintain, and repair electrical wiring, equipment, and fixtures. Ensure that work is in accordance with relevant codes. May install or service street lights, intercom systems, or electrical control systems. Excludes “Security and Fire Alarm Systems Installers” (49-2098).

title: Glaziers
def: Install glass in windows, skylights, store fronts, and display cases, or on surfaces, such as building fronts, interior walls, ceilings, and tabletops.

title: Insulation workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Insulation workers, floor, etc
soc_title: Insulation Workers, Floor, Ceiling, and Wall
def: Line and cover structures with insulating materials. May work with batt, roll, or blown insulation materials.

title: Insulation workers, mechanical
def: Apply insulating materials to pipes or ductwork, or other mechanical systems in order to help control and maintain temperature.

title: Painters and paperhangers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Painters, construction and maintenance
def: Paint walls, equipment, buildings, bridges, and other structural surfaces, using brushes, rollers, and spray guns. May remove old paint to prepare surface prior to painting. May mix colors or oils to obtain desired color or consistency. Excludes “Paperhangers” (47-2142).

title: Paperhangers
def: Cover interior walls or ceilings of rooms with decorative wallpaper or fabric, or attach advertising posters on surfaces such as walls and billboards. May remove old materials or prepare surfaces to be papered.

title: Pipelayers, plumbers, etc
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Pipelayers
def: Lay pipe for storm or sanitation sewers, drains, and water mains. Perform any combination of the following tasks: grade trenches or culverts, position pipe, or seal joints. Excludes “Welders, Cutters, Solderers, and Brazers” (51-4121).

title: Plumbers, pipefitters, etc
def: Assemble, install, alter, and repair pipelines or pipe systems that carry water, steam, air, or other liquids or gases. May install heating and cooling equipment and mechanical control systems. Includes sprinkler fitters.

title: Plasterers and stucco masons
def: Apply interior or exterior plaster, cement, stucco, or similar materials. May also set ornamental plaster.

title: Reinforcing iron and rebar workers
def: Position and secure steel bars or mesh in concrete forms in order to reinforce concrete. Use a variety of fasteners, rod-bending machines, blowtorches, and hand tools. Includes rod busters.

title: Roofers
def: Cover roofs of structures with shingles, slate, asphalt, aluminum, wood, or related materials. May spray roofs, sidings, and walls with material to bind, seal, insulate, or soundproof sections of structures.

title: Sheet metal workers
def: Fabricate, assemble, install, and repair sheet metal products and equipment, such as ducts, control boxes, drainpipes, and furnace casings. Work may involve any of the following: setting up and operating fabricating machines to cut, bend, and straighten sheet metal; shaping metal over anvils, blocks, or forms using hammer; operating soldering and welding equipment to join sheet metal parts; or inspecting, assembling, and smoothing seams and joints of burred surfaces. Includes sheet metal duct installers who install prefabricated sheet metal ducts used for heating, air conditioning, or other purposes.

title: Structural iron and steel workers
def: Raise, place, and unite iron or steel girders, columns, and other structural members to form completed structures or structural frameworks. May erect metal storage tanks and assemble prefabricated metal buildings. Excludes “Reinforcing Iron and Rebar Workers” (47-2171).

title: Solar photovoltaic installers
def: Assemble, install, or maintain solar photovoltaic (PV) systems on roofs or other structures in compliance with site assessment and schematics. May include measuring, cutting, assembling, and bolting structural framing and solar modules. May perform minor electrical work such as current checks. Excludes solar PV electricians who are included in “Electricians” (47-2111) and solar thermal installers who are included in “Plumbers, Pipefitters, and Steamfitters” (47-2152).

title: Helpers, construction trades
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Helpers--brickmasons, blockmasons, etc
soc_title: Helpers--Brickmasons, Blockmasons, Stonemasons, and Tile and Marble Setters
def: Help brickmasons, blockmasons, stonemasons, or tile and marble setters by performing duties requiring less skill. Duties include using, supplying, or holding materials or tools, and cleaning work area and equipment. Construction laborers who do not primarily assist brickmasons, blockmasons, and stonemasons or tile and marble setters are classified under “Construction Laborers” (47-2061). Apprentice workers are classified with the appropriate skilled construction trade occupation (47-2011 through 47-2231).

title: Helpers--carpenters
def: Help carpenters by performing duties requiring less skill. Duties include using, supplying, or holding materials or tools, and cleaning work area and equipment. Construction laborers who do not primarily assist carpenters are classified under “Construction Laborers” (47-2061). Apprentice workers are classified with the appropriate skilled construction trade occupation (47-2011 through 47-2231).

title: Helpers--electricians
def: Help electricians by performing duties requiring less skill. Duties include using, supplying, or holding materials or tools, and cleaning work area and equipment. Construction laborers who do not primarily assist electricians are classified under “Construction Laborers” (47-2061). Apprentice workers are classified with the appropriate skilled construction trade occupation (47-2011 through 47-2231).

title: Helpers--painters, paperhangers, etc
soc_title: Helpers--Painters, Paperhangers, Plasterers, and Stucco Masons
def: Help painters, paperhangers, plasterers, or stucco masons by performing duties requiring less skill. Duties include using, supplying, or holding materials or tools, and cleaning work area and equipment. Construction laborers who do not primarily assist painters, paperhangers, plasterers, or stucco masons are classified under “Construction Laborers” (47-2061). Apprentice workers are classified with the appropriate skilled construction trade occupation (47-2011 through 47-2231).

title: Helpers--pipelayers, plumbers, etc
def: Help plumbers, pipefitters, steamfitters, or pipelayers by performing duties requiring less skill. Duties include using, supplying, or holding materials or tools, and cleaning work area and equipment. Construction laborers who do not primarily assist plumbers, pipefitters, steamfitters, or pipelayers are classified under “Construction Laborers” (47-2061). Apprentice workers are classified with the appropriate skilled construction trade occupation (47-2011 through 47-2231).

title: Helpers--roofers
def: Help roofers by performing duties requiring less skill. Duties include using, supplying, or holding materials or tools, and cleaning work area and equipment. Construction laborers who do not primarily assist roofers are classified under “Construction Laborers” (47-2061). Apprentice workers are classified with the appropriate skilled construction trade occupation (47-2011 through 47-2231).

title: Helpers, construction trades, etc
def: All construction trades helpers not listed separately.

title: Other construction and related workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Construction and building inspectors
def: Inspect structures using engineering skills to determine structural soundness and compliance with specifications, building codes, and other regulations. Inspections may be general in nature or may be limited to a specific area, such as electrical systems or plumbing.

title: Elevator and escalator installers and repairers
soc_title: Elevator and Escalator Installers and Repairers
def: Assemble, install, repair, or maintain electric or hydraulic freight or passenger elevators, escalators, or dumbwaiters.

title: Fence erectors
def: Erect and repair fences and fence gates, using hand and power tools.

title: Hazardous materials removal workers
def: Identify, remove, pack, transport, or dispose of hazardous materials, including asbestos, lead-based paint, waste oil, fuel, transmission fluid, radioactive materials, or contaminated soil. Specialized training and certification in hazardous materials handling or a confined entry permit are generally required. May operate earth-moving equipment or trucks.

title: Highway maintenance workers
def: Maintain highways, municipal and rural roads, airport runways, and rights-of-way. Duties include patching broken or eroded pavement and repairing guard rails, highway markers, and snow fences. May also mow or clear brush from along road, or plow snow from roadway. Excludes “Tree Trimmers and Pruners” (37-3013).

title: Rail-track laying and maintenance equipment operators
soc_title: Rail-Track Laying and Maintenance Equipment Operators
def: Lay, repair, and maintain track for standard or narrow-gauge railroad equipment used in regular railroad service or in plant yards, quarries, sand and gravel pits, and mines. Includes ballast cleaning machine operators and railroad bed tamping machine operators.

title: Septic tank servicers and sewer pipe cleaners
soc_title: Septic Tank Servicers and Sewer Pipe Cleaners
def: Clean and repair septic tanks, sewer lines, or drains. May patch walls and partitions of tank, replace damaged drain tile, or repair breaks in underground piping.

title: Miscellaneous construction and related workers
def: No job definition found.

title: Extraction workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Derrick, rotary drill, etc
soc_title: Derrick, Rotary Drill, and Service Unit Operators, Oil and Gas
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Derrick operators, oil and gas
def: Rig derrick equipment and operate pumps to circulate mud or fluid through drill hole.

title: Rotary drill operators, oil and gas
soc_title: Rotary Drill Operators, Oil and Gas
def: Set up or operate a variety of drills to remove underground oil and gas, or remove core samples for testing during oil and gas exploration. Excludes “Earth Drillers, Except Oil and Gas” (47-5023).

title: Service unit operators, oil and gas
soc_title: Service Unit Operators, Oil and Gas
def: Operate equipment to increase oil flow from producing wells or to remove stuck pipe, casing, tools, or other obstructions from drilling wells. Includes fishing-tool technicians.

title: Surface mining machine operators and earth drillers
soc_title: Surface Mining Machine Operators and Earth Drillers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Excavating and loading machine and dragline operators, surface mining
soc_title: Excavating and Loading Machine and Dragline Operators, Surface Mining
def: Operate or tend machinery at surface mining site, equipped with scoops, shovels, or buckets to excavate and load loose materials.

title: Earth drillers, except oil and gas
soc_title: Earth Drillers, Except Oil and Gas
def: Operate a variety of drills such as rotary, churn, and pneumatic to tap subsurface water and salt deposits, to remove core samples during mineral exploration or soil testing, and to facilitate the use of explosives in mining or construction. Includes horizontal and earth boring machine operators.

title: Explosives workers, ordnance handling experts, etc
soc_title: Explosives Workers, Ordnance Handling Experts, and Blasters
def: Place and detonate explosives to demolish structures or to loosen, remove, or displace earth, rock, or other materials. May perform specialized handling, storage, and accounting procedures.

title: Underground mining machine operators
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Continuous mining machine operators
def: Operate self-propelled mining machines that rip coal, metal and nonmetal ores, rock, stone, or sand from the mine face and load it onto conveyors, shuttle cars, or trucks in a continuous operation.

title: Roof bolters, mining
def: Operate machinery to install roof support bolts in underground mine.

title: Loading and moving machine operators, underground mining
soc_title: Loading and Moving Machine Operators, Underground Mining
def: Operate underground loading or moving machine to load or move coal, ore, or rock using shuttle or mine car or conveyors. Equipment may include power shovels, hoisting engines equipped with cable-drawn scraper or scoop, or machines equipped with gathering arms and conveyor.

title: Underground mining machine operators, all other
soc_title: Underground Mining Machine Operators, All Other
def: All underground mining machine operators not listed separately.

title: Rock splitters, quarry
def: Separate blocks of rough dimension stone from quarry mass using jackhammers, wedges, or chop saws.

title: Roustabouts, oil and gas
def: Assemble or repair oil field equipment using hand and power tools. Perform other tasks as needed.

title: Helpers--extraction workers
def: Help extraction craft workers, such as earth drillers, blasters and explosives workers, derrick operators, and mining machine operators, by performing duties requiring less skill. Duties include supplying equipment or cleaning work area. Apprentice workers are classified with the appropriate skilled construction trade occupation (47-2011 through 47-2231).

title: Extraction workers, all other
def: All extraction workers not listed separately.

title: Installation, maintenance, etc
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Supervisors of installation, maintenance, etc
soc_title: Supervisors of Installation, Maintenance, and Repair Workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: First-line supervisors of mechanics, installers, etc
soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Mechanics, Installers, and Repairers
def: Directly supervise and coordinate the activities of mechanics, installers, and repairers. May also advise customers on recommended services. Excludes team or work leaders.

title: Electrical and electronic equipment mechanics, installers, etc
soc_title: Electrical and Electronic Equipment Mechanics, Installers, and Repairers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Computer, automated teller, etc
soc_title: Computer, Automated Teller, and Office Machine Repairers
def: Repair, maintain, or install computers, word processing systems, automated teller machines, and electronic office machines, such as duplicating and fax machines.

title: Radio and telecommunications equipment installers and repairers
soc_title: Radio and Telecommunications Equipment Installers and Repairers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Radio, cellular, etc
soc_title: Radio, Cellular, and Tower Equipment Installers and Repairers
def: Repair, install, or maintain mobile or stationary radio transmitting, broadcasting, and receiving equipment, and two-way radio communications systems used in cellular telecommunications, mobile broadband, ship-to-shore, aircraft-to-ground communications, and radio equipment in service and emergency vehicles. May test and analyze network coverage.

title: Telecommunications equipment installers and repairers, except line installers
soc_title: Telecommunications Equipment Installers and Repairers, Except Line Installers
def: Install, set up, rearrange, or remove switching, distribution, routing, and dialing equipment used in central offices or headends. Service or repair telephone, cable television, Internet, and other communications equipment on customers’ property. May install communications equipment or communications wiring in buildings. Excludes “Telecommunications Line Installers and Repairers” (49-9052).

title: Miscellaneous electrical and electronic equipment mechanics, installers, etc
soc_title: Miscellaneous Electrical and Electronic Equipment Mechanics, Installers, and Repairers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Avionics technicians
def: Install, inspect, test, adjust, or repair avionics equipment, such as radar, radio, navigation, and missile control systems in aircraft or space vehicles.

title: Electric motor, power tool, etc
soc_title: Electric Motor, Power Tool, and Related Repairers
def: Repair, maintain, or install electric motors, wiring, or switches.

title: Electrical and electronics installers and repairers, transportation equipment
soc_title: Electrical and Electronics Installers and Repairers, Transportation Equipment
def: Install, adjust, or maintain mobile electronics communication equipment, including sound, sonar, security, navigation, and surveillance systems on trains, watercraft, or other mobile equipment. Excludes “Avionics Technicians” (49-2091) and “Electronic Equipment Installers and Repairers, Motor Vehicles” (49-2096).

title: Electrical and electronics repairers, commercial and industrial equipment
soc_title: Electrical and Electronics Repairers, Commercial and Industrial Equipment
def: Repair, test, adjust, or install electronic equipment, such as industrial controls, transmitters, and antennas. Excludes “Avionics Technicians” (49-2091), “Electrical and Electronics Installers and Repairers, Transportation Equipment” (49-2093), and “Electronic Equipment Installers and Repairers, Motor Vehicles” (49-2096).

title: Electrical and electronics repairers, powerhouse, etc
soc_title: Electrical and Electronics Repairers, Powerhouse, Substation, and Relay
def: Inspect, test, repair, or maintain electrical equipment in generating stations, substations, and in-service relays.

title: Electronic equipment installers and repairers, motor vehicles
soc_title: Electronic Equipment Installers and Repairers, Motor Vehicles
def: Install, diagnose, or repair communications, sound, security, or navigation equipment in motor vehicles.

title: Audiovisual equipment installers and repairers
def: Install, repair, or adjust audio or television receivers, stereo systems, camcorders, video systems, or other electronic entertainment equipment in homes or other venues. May perform routine maintenance. Excludes “Audio and Video Technicians” (27-4011).

title: Security and fire alarm systems installers
soc_title: Security and Fire Alarm Systems Installers
def: Install, program, maintain, and repair security and fire alarm wiring and equipment. Ensure that work is in accordance with relevant codes. Excludes “Electricians” (47-2111) who do a broad range of electrical wiring.

title: Vehicle and mobile equipment mechanics, installers, etc
soc_title: Vehicle and Mobile Equipment Mechanics, Installers, and Repairers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Aircraft mechanics and service technicians
def: Diagnose, adjust, repair, or overhaul aircraft engines and assemblies, such as hydraulic and pneumatic systems. Excludes “Avionics Technicians” (49-2091).

title: Automotive technicians and repairers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Automotive body and related repairers
def: Repair and refinish automotive vehicle bodies and straighten vehicle frames. Excludes “Automotive Glass Installers and Repairers” (49-3022) and “Coating, Painting, and Spraying Machine Setters, Operators, and Tenders” (51-9124).

title: Automotive glass installers and repairers
def: Replace or repair broken windshields and window glass in motor vehicles.

title: Automotive service technicians and mechanics
def: Diagnose, adjust, repair, or overhaul automotive vehicles. Excludes “Automotive Body and Related Repairers” (49-3021), “Bus and Truck Mechanics and Diesel Engine Specialists” (49-3031), and “Electronic Equipment Installers and Repairers, Motor Vehicles” (49-2096).

title: Bus and truck mechanics and diesel engine specialists
soc_title: Bus and Truck Mechanics and Diesel Engine Specialists
def: Diagnose, adjust, repair, or overhaul buses and trucks, or maintain and repair any type of diesel engines. Includes mechanics working primarily with automobile or marine diesel engines.

title: Heavy vehicle and mobile equipment service technicians and mechanics
soc_title: Heavy Vehicle and Mobile Equipment Service Technicians and Mechanics
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Farm equipment mechanics and service technicians
soc_title: Farm Equipment Mechanics and Service Technicians
def: Diagnose, adjust, repair, or overhaul farm machinery and vehicles, such as tractors, harvesters, dairy equipment, and irrigation systems. Excludes “Bus and Truck Mechanics and Diesel Engine Specialists” (49-3031).

title: Mobile heavy equipment mechanics, except engines
soc_title: Mobile Heavy Equipment Mechanics, Except Engines
def: Diagnose, adjust, repair, or overhaul mobile mechanical, hydraulic, and pneumatic equipment, such as cranes, bulldozers, graders, and conveyors, used in construction, logging, and mining. Excludes “Bus and Truck Mechanics and Diesel Engine Specialists” (49-3031) and “Rail Car Repairers” (49-3043).

title: Rail car repairers
def: Diagnose, adjust, repair, or overhaul railroad rolling stock, mine cars, or mass transit rail cars. Excludes “Bus and Truck Mechanics and Diesel Engine Specialists” (49-3031).

title: Small engine mechanics
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Motorboat mechanics and service technicians
def: Repair and adjust electrical and mechanical equipment of inboard or inboard-outboard boat engines. Excludes “Bus and Truck Mechanics and Diesel Engine Specialists” (49-3031).

title: Motorcycle mechanics
def: Diagnose, adjust, repair, or overhaul motorcycles, scooters, mopeds, dirt bikes, or similar motorized vehicles.

title: Outdoor power equipment and other small engine mechanics
soc_title: Outdoor Power Equipment and Other Small Engine Mechanics
def: Diagnose, adjust, repair, or overhaul small engines used to power lawn mowers, chain saws, recreational sporting equipment, and related equipment.

title: Miscellaneous vehicle and mobile equipment mechanics, installers, etc
soc_title: Miscellaneous Vehicle and Mobile Equipment Mechanics, Installers, and Repairers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Bicycle repairers
def: Repair and service bicycles.

title: Recreational vehicle service technicians
def: Diagnose, inspect, adjust, repair, or overhaul recreational vehicles including travel trailers. May specialize in maintaining gas, electrical, hydraulic, plumbing, or chassis/towing systems as well as repairing generators, appliances, and interior components. Includes workers who perform customized van conversions. Excludes “Automotive Service Technicians and Mechanics” (49-3023) and “Bus and Truck Mechanics and Diesel Engine Specialists” (49-3031) who also work on recreation vehicles.

title: Tire repairers and changers
def: Repair and replace tires.

title: Other installation, maintenance, etc
soc_title: Other Installation, Maintenance, and Repair Occupations
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Control and valve installers and repairers
soc_title: Control and Valve Installers and Repairers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Mechanical door repairers
def: Install, service, or repair automatic door mechanisms and hydraulic doors. Includes garage door mechanics.

title: Control and valve installers and repairers, except mechanical door
soc_title: Control and Valve Installers and Repairers, Except Mechanical Door
def: Install, repair, and maintain mechanical regulating and controlling devices, such as electric meters, gas regulators, thermostats, safety and flow valves, and other mechanical governors.

title: Heating, air conditioning, etc
soc_title: Heating, Air Conditioning, and Refrigeration Mechanics and Installers
def: Install or repair heating, central air conditioning, HVAC, or refrigeration systems, including oil burners, hot-air furnaces, and heating stoves.

title: Home appliance repairers
def: Repair, adjust, or install all types of electric or gas household appliances, such as refrigerators, washers, dryers, and ovens.

title: Industrial machinery installation, repair, etc
soc_title: Industrial Machinery Installation, Repair, and Maintenance Workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Industrial machinery mechanics
def: Repair, install, adjust, or maintain industrial production and processing machinery or refinery and pipeline distribution systems. May also install, dismantle, or move machinery and heavy equipment according to plans. Excludes “Mobile Heavy Equipment Mechanics, Except Engines” (49-3042), and “Maintenance Workers, Machinery” (49-9043).

title: Maintenance workers, machinery
def: Lubricate machinery, change parts, or perform other routine machinery maintenance. Excludes “Maintenance and Repair Workers, General” (49-9071).

title: Millwrights
def: Install, dismantle, or move machinery and heavy equipment according to layout plans, blueprints, or other drawings.

title: Refractory materials repairers, except brickmasons
def: Build or repair equipment such as furnaces, kilns, cupolas, boilers, converters, ladles, soaking pits, and ovens, using refractory materials.

title: Line installers and repairers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Electrical power-line installers and repairers
def: Install or repair cables or wires used in electrical power or distribution systems. May erect poles and light or heavy duty transmission towers. Excludes “Electrical and Electronics Repairers, Powerhouse, Substation, and Relay” (49-2095).

title: Telecommunications line installers and repairers
def: Install and repair telecommunications cable, including fiber optics.

title: Precision instrument and equipment repairers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Camera and photographic equipment repairers
def: Repair and adjust cameras and photographic equipment, including commercial video and motion picture camera equipment.

title: Medical equipment repairers
def: Test, adjust, or repair biomedical or electromedical equipment.

title: Musical instrument repairers and tuners
def: Repair percussion, stringed, reed, or wind instruments. May specialize in one area, such as piano tuning. Excludes “Audiovisual Equipment Installers and Repairers" (49-2097) who repair electrical and electronic musical instruments.

title: Watch and clock repairers
def: Repair, clean, and adjust mechanisms of timing instruments, such as watches and clocks. Includes watchmakers, watch technicians, and mechanical timepiece repairers. Excludes "Timing Device Assemblers and Adjusters” (51-2061).

title: Precision instrument and equipment repairers, all other
soc_title: Precision Instrument and Equipment Repairers, All Other
def: All precision instrument and equipment repairers not listed separately.

title: Maintenance and repair workers, general
def: Perform work involving the skills of two or more maintenance or craft occupations to keep machines, mechanical equipment, or the structure of a building in repair. Duties may involve pipe fitting; HVAC maintenance; insulating; welding; machining; carpentry; repairing electrical or mechanical equipment; installing, aligning, and balancing new equipment; and repairing buildings, floors, or stairs. Excludes “Facilities Managers” (11-3013) and “Maintenance Workers, Machinery” (49-9043).

title: Wind turbine service technicians
def: Inspect, diagnose, adjust, or repair wind turbines. Perform maintenance on wind turbine equipment including resolving electrical, mechanical, and hydraulic malfunctions.

title: Miscellaneous installation, maintenance, etc
soc_title: Miscellaneous Installation, Maintenance, and Repair Workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Coin, vending, etc
soc_title: Coin, Vending, and Amusement Machine Servicers and Repairers
def: Install, service, adjust, or repair coin, vending, or amusement machines including video games, juke boxes, pinball machines, or slot machines.

title: Commercial divers
def: Work below surface of water, using surface-supplied air or scuba equipment to inspect, repair, remove, or install equipment and structures. May use a variety of power and hand tools, such as drills, sledgehammers, torches, and welding equipment. May conduct tests or experiments, rig explosives, or photograph structures or marine life. Excludes “Athletes and Sports Competitors” (27-2021), “Police and Sheriff’s Patrol Officers” (33-3051), and “Fishing and Hunting Workers” (45-3031).

title: Locksmiths and safe repairers
def: Repair and open locks, make keys, change locks and safe combinations, and install and repair safes.

title: Manufactured building and mobile home installers
soc_title: Manufactured Building and Mobile Home Installers
def: Move or install mobile homes or prefabricated buildings.

title: Riggers
def: Set up or repair rigging for construction projects, manufacturing plants, logging yards, ships and shipyards, or for the entertainment industry.

title: Signal and track switch repairers
def: Install, inspect, test, maintain, or repair electric gate crossings, signals, signal equipment, track switches, section lines, or intercommunications systems within a railroad system.

title: Helpers--installation, maintenance, etc
def: Help installation, maintenance, and repair workers in maintenance, parts replacement, and repair of vehicles, industrial machinery, and electrical and electronic equipment. Perform duties such as furnishing tools, materials, and supplies to other workers; cleaning work area, machines, and tools; and holding materials or tools for other workers.

title: Installation, maintenance, etc
soc_title: Installation, Maintenance, and Repair Workers, All Other
def: All installation, maintenance, and repair workers not listed separately.

title: Production Occupations
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Supervisors of production workers
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: First-line supervisors of production and operating workers
soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Production and Operating Workers
def: Directly supervise and coordinate the activities of production and operating workers, such as inspectors, precision workers, machine setters and operators, assemblers, fabricators, and plant and system operators. Excludes team or work leaders.

title: Assemblers and fabricators
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Aircraft structure, surfaces, etc
soc_title: Aircraft Structure, Surfaces, Rigging, and Systems Assemblers
def: Assemble, fit, fasten, and install parts of airplanes, space vehicles, or missiles, such as tails, wings, fuselage, bulkheads, stabilizers, landing gear, rigging and control equipment, or heating and ventilating systems.

title: Electrical, electronics, etc
def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

title: Coil winders, tapers, etc
def: Wind wire coils used in electrical components, such as resistors and transformers, and in electrical equipment and instruments, such as field cores, bobbins, armature cores, electrical motors, generators, and control equipment.

title: Electrical, electronic, etc
def: No job definition found.

title: Engine and other machine assemblers
def: Construct, assemble, or rebuild machines, such as engines, turbines, and similar equipment used in such industries as construction, extraction, textiles, and paper manufacturing.

title: Structural metal fabricators and fitters
def: Fabricate, position, align, and fit parts of structural metal products. Shipfitters are included in “Layout Workers, Metal and Plastic” (51-4192).
